  "event_preview": "Texas Motor Speedway is a 1.5-mile (2.414 km) quad-oval in Fort Worth, Texas, repaved and reconfigured in 2017 — when Turns 1 and 2 were reduced from 24 to 20 degrees of banking while Turns 3 and 4 retained 24 degrees, creating the asymmetric character that defines the current layout. The Andy's Frozen Custard 340 is the twelfth race of the 2026 NASCAR O'Reilly Auto Parts Series season, run over 200 laps (300 miles) with stage breaks at laps 45 and 90. It is also the final race of the Dash 4 Cash series, with the $100,000 bonus on the line for the top four eligible regulars after qualifying at Talladega.\n\nJustin Allgaier leads the 2026 championship standings with 544 points, 105 ahead of Sheldon Creed in second. Connor Zilisch and Kyle Larson both enter in JR Motorsports machinery — Larson seeking a Texas win to add to a resume of dominance at the track that includes 10 O'Reilly Series victories, the most of any driver in series history here. Corey Day, fresh off his first career series win at Talladega the previous weekend, returns in the No. 17 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet. Austin Dillon also makes a notable entry in the No. 3 Richard Childress Racing car. With 38 entries for 38 available positions, the full field is set to start.\n\nThe all-time O'Reilly Series qualifying lap record at Texas belongs to Ryan Blaney, who turned a 28.342-second lap in 2018 — set on the post-repave surface. The race lap record belongs to Kyle Busch, set at 151.707 mph average on April 5, 2008.",
